					<msContents>
						<summary>

						<p>At the entrance into the Naṭarāja shrine in the same temple, right side.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājakēsarivarman</hi> <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> <hi rend="bold">Uḍaiyār śrī-Rājādhirājadēva (I): Year 33, 1050-51 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription is damaged at the end. It refers to the king as who took the head of Vīrapāṇḍya, the head of the Chēraṉ (?) and Ilaṅkai (Laṅkā = Ceylon).</p>						

						<p>It records a gift of 4 <hi rend="italic">kāśu</hi> for burning a <hi rend="italic">sandhi</hi> lamp during night in the temple of the god Uttamaśōḻaviṇṇagar Āḻvār of Tirunallam, a <hi rend="italic">Brahmadēśam,</hi> in Veṇṇāḍu in Uyyakkoṇḍār-vaḷanāḍu, by a certain <hi rend="italic">Brāhmaṇa</hi> named Māḍalaṉ Tirumāliruñjōlai Śrīkārimāṟan and that the money was received by a certain Vaikāṉasan Kāśyapaṉ-Kētaḷan Gōvindan, who was probably a priest of the temple, who has agreed to burn the lamp. </p>						

						</summary>
